  <title>STL</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword>STL</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1" style="width:450px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">A <text styleclass="Popup Box2">STL</text> file-type is derived from the word &quot;Stereo-lithography.&quot; The <text styleclass="Popup Box2">STL</text> file-type gives the xyz coordinates of the vertices and normals of triangles that describe the surface of the 3D object.</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">Each triangle is defined by its normal and three points at its vertices. You can have a coarse, fine or custom number of triangles and vertices.</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">The number of triangles you need is a balance between unmanageable file size (too many triangles) and a well-defined model with reasonably smooth curved geometries.</para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#993300;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">The <text styleclass="Popup Box2">STL </text>File should be saved as a Binary file with units of Meters</para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
</topic>
